A guide to genome QC and viz with GENESPACE

JT Lovell

2023-04-12

1. Overview

Starting with v1.2.0, GENESPACE offers genome quality control and visualization tools outside of the standard pipeline for syntenic orthology.

The main added functionality fall into three groups:

  1. Kmer finding, parsing and plotting (e.g.telomeres, gaps)
  2. Sliding window analysis of intervals (e.g.genes, repeats)
  3. Contig and telomere position plotting.

2. Using GENESPACE for genome viz

Unlike the syntenic orthology methods, the routines here do not require any third party programs aside from a few R packages (you dont need to install MCScanX, OrthoFinder, etc.).

However, you will need the following additional packages: GenomicRanges, GenomeInfoDb, IRanges, and BiocGenerics. These can be downloaded from Bioconductor as follows:

if (!require("BiocManager", quietly = TRUE))
    install.packages("BiocManager")

BiocManager::install(
  c("BiocGenerics", "IRanges", "GenomicRanges", "GenomeInfoDb", "rtracklayer")

So, to get started, you can just open an R session however you would normally, install GENESPACE (if you havent or have a version < 1.2.0) and load it into R.

if(!require("GENESPACE", quietly = TRUE)){
  devtools::install_github("jtlovell/GENESPACE", upgrade = F)
}else{
  gsv <- as.numeric(strsplit(as.character(
    packageVersion("GENESPACE")), ".", fixed = T)[[1]])
  if(gsv[1] < 1 || (gsv[1] >= 1 & gsv[2] < 2)){
    detach("package:GENESPACE", unload = TRUE)
    devtools::install_github("jtlovell/GENESPACE", upgrade = F)
  }
}
## GENESPACE v1.2.0: synteny and orthology constrained comparative
##         genomics
library(GENESPACE)

For this tutorial, we also need to load a few other packages for plotting and data wrangling 

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(data.table))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(Biostrings))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(ggplot2))

3. Input data

There are three types of data that GENESPACE genome viz can handle:

  1. Soft- or un-masked genome assembly fasta
  2. Genomic intervals (e.g.bed or gff-formatted annotations)
  3. kmer fasta files

Unlike the main GENESPACE pipeline, there is a bit of scripting that is required for viz.Specifically, youll need to read your source files in and get them into a format that GENESPACE likes.

Here, well illustrate the functionality with the Hg38 human genomes. Specifically, well make contig maps, then do sliding windows with gene and repeat gff files.

To start, make a new directory to put the files, then download them there:

wd <- "~/Downloads/vizTest"
if(!dir.exists(wd))
  dir.create(wd)

gffFile <- file.path(wd, "GRCh38_latest_genomic.gff.gz")
faFile <- file.path(wd, "GRCh38_latest_genomic.fna.gz")

url <- "https://ftp.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/refseq/H_sapiens/annotation/GRCh38_latest/refseq_identifiers/"

if(!file.exists(gffFile))
  tmp <- download.file(
    file.path(url, "GRCh38_latest_genomic.gff.gz"), 
    destfile = gffFile)

if(!file.exists(faFile))
  tmp <- download.file(
    file.path(url, "GRCh38_latest_genomic.fna.gz"), 
    destfile = faFile)

Then we can read these files into R memory. This can be a pretty big lift for some machines and some large genomes.

dnaSS <- Biostrings::readDNAStringSet(faFile)

We also only want to show the main chromosomes (not all the unlocalized scaffolds). To drop these, we need to do a little parsing:

ns <- names(dnaSS)
ns <- ns[!grepl("unlocalized|RANDOM", ns) & # drop chrs with these terms
           grepl("GRCh38.p14 Primary Assembly", ns)] # keep chrs with these
dnaSS <- dnaSS[ns]

# -- parse the chromosome names so they are better for plotting ...
names(dnaSS) <- sapply(names(dnaSS), function(x) strsplit(x, " ")[[1]][[5]])
names(dnaSS) <- gsub(",", "", names(dnaSS), fixed = T)

4. Make the contig map

One of the most useful things to know about your genome is where are the gaps. In most genomes, gaps come between two contigs, and GENESPACE infers contigs and any sequences separated by >= `` Ns.

The function find_contigsGapsTelos finds these gaps and also locates telomeres. The structure and identity of telomeres varies considerably by taxonomic group and assembly method. As such, we allow three parameters to vary when looking for telomeres:

  • teloKmers: the repeated sequences that indicate the presence of a telomere. These and their reverse compliments are used.
  • maxDistBtwTelo: the maximum distance in base pairs within a single telomere sequence between two exact matches of the telomere kmers. Larger gaps mean that the telomere is split into multiple intervals.
  • minTeloSize: the minimum size in base pairs for a sequence to be considered a telomere
  • minTeloDens: the minimum proportion of sequence in a telomere that exactly matches one or more of the kmers.

This function also drops small contigs/scaffolds to make visualization and summary stats clearer. To adjust this value, use minChrSize.

humanTelomereKmers <- "TTAGGG"
genomeGrs <- find_contigsGapsTelos(
  dnass = dnaSS,
  teloKmers = humanTelomereKmers,
  maxDistBtwTelo = 500,
  minTeloSize = 100,
  minTeloDens = .9,
  maxDist2end = 50e3,
  minChrSize = 1e6, 
  minContigGapSize = 1000)
##         N. scaffolds = 24 (N50 = 156.04Mb); total length = 3088.27Mb
##         N. contigs = 867 (N50 = 52.37Mb); total length = 2937.64Mb
##         N. telomeres = 5 (1.81kb) on chrs: 5L, 7LR, 18I, 21R
print(lapply(genomeGrs, head))

The reported values are for sequences in the fasta. In this case these are the chromosomes, but may also be scaffolds. Contigs are here defined as sub-sequences in the chromosomes separated by consecutive runs of >= 1,000 Ns, as specified in minContigGapSize. Telomeres are categories as on the right (R) or left (L) terminus if they are within maxDist2end of the very end of the chromosome. Here, setting this to 50kb since some chromosomes have long runs of Ns at the termini.

The output is a list of genomic ranges (GR), which can be plotted with the GENESPACE function plot_contigs. This can take a single contigGapTelomere (cgt) or a named list of cgts to make a multi-paneled figure.

plot_contigs(
  cgt = genomeGrs,
  nColors = 20,
  palette = viridis::viridis)

5. Sliding window of proportion of sequence in intervals

Sliding windows are a useful way to summarize the large and complex data stored in a genome. One standard way of presenting this data is by showing gene and repeat densities. Here, well illustrate how to do this using GENESPACE functionality.

First, we need to make bed-like (or GRange objects containing the intervals of interest). Here well focus on CDS, transcripts, LINE/SINE, LTR, Satellite and other repeats.

First, download the T2T annotation and assembly files:

faFile <- file.path(wd, "chm13v2.0.fa.gz")
geneGffFile <- file.path(wd, "chm13v2.0_RefSeq_Liftoff_v4.gff3")
repBedFile <- file.path(wd, "chm13v2.0_RepeatMasker_4.1.2p1.2022Apr14.bed")
url <- "https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/human-pangenomics/T2T/CHM13/assemblies"

if(!file.exists(geneGffFile))
  tmp <- download.file(
    file.path(url, "annotation/chm13v2.0_RefSeq_Liftoff_v4.gff3"), 
    destfile = geneGffFile)

if(!file.exists(repBedFile))
  tmp <- download.file(
    file.path(url, "annotation/chm13v2.0_RepeatMasker_4.1.2p1.2022Apr14.bed"), 
    destfile = repBedFile)

if(!file.exists(faFile))
  tmp <- download.file(
    file.path(url, "analysis_set/chm13v2.0.fa.gz"), 
    destfile = faFile)

Then, read in these data into R 

dnaSS <- Biostrings::readDNAStringSet(faFile)
names(dnaSS) <- sapply(names(dnaSS), function(x) strsplit(x, " ")[[1]][1])
dnaSS <- dnaSS[Biostrings::width(dnaSS) > 1e6]
seqInfo <- pull_seqInfo(dnaSS)

genes <- as.data.frame(rtracklayer::readGFF(
  geneGffFile,
  columns = c("seqid", "start", "end", "type"), 
  tags = "Parent", 
  filter = list(type = c("transcript", "exon"))))
genes <- subset(genes, seqid %in% names(dnaSS))

library(data.table)
repeats <- fread(
  repBedFile, 
  select = c(1:3, 7),
  col.names = c("chr", "start", "end", "type"))
repeats <- subset(repeats, chr %in% names(dnaSS))

Combine the datasets into a list of bed-like objects (with chr, start, end columns) 

bedList <- list(
  exon = with(subset(genes, type == "exon"), data.frame(
    chr = seqid, start = start, end = end)),
  LINE.SINE = with(subset(repeats, grepl("LINE|SINE", type)), data.frame(
    chr = chr, start = start, end = end)),
  LTR = with(subset(repeats, grepl("LTR", type)), data.frame(
    chr = chr, start = start, end = end)),
  Satellite = with(subset(repeats, grepl("Satellite", type)), data.frame(
    chr = chr, start = start, end = end)),
  otherRepeat = with(subset(repeats, !grepl("LINE|SINE|Satellite|LTR", type)), data.frame(
    chr = chr, start = start, end = end)),
  introns = with(subset(genes, type == "transcript"), data.frame(
    chr = seqid, start = start, end = end)))
print(lapply(bedList, head))

The function classify_genome takes this list of bed objects and hierarchically classifies the genomes in the order the bed objects are provided. So, here, first all exon sequences are found and overlapping ranges are joined. This exon sequence is then masked from the genome and the repeats regions are inferred, sequentially masking any sequence already there. Finally, un-classified sequence intervals are found.

suppressWarnings(genomeClasses <- classify_genome(
  dnaSS = dnaSS, listOfBeds = bedList, verbose = T))
##  (3117.28 Mb in 24 chrs)

With a hierarchical classification of the genome in hand, we can use slide_genome to ask about the relative abundance of each class in a given window.

sws <- slide_genome(
  seqInfo = seqInfo,
  listOfGrs = genomeClasses[c(1,6,7,2,3,4,5)],
  windowSize = 5e6,
  stepSize = 1e6)
head(sws)
##     chr start     end     nBp        id nBpWindow  propWind   cumProp
## 1: chr1     1 5000000  533430      exon     5e+06 0.1066860 0.1066860

## 3: chr1     1 5000000 1089047   unknown     5e+06 0.2178094 0.6253662

The output data.table (see above) can then be easily plotted in ggplot2 using geom_area.

library(ggplot2)
plotCols <- c("#CC6828", "#F4A460", "#FFFFFF", "#0F4F8B", "#4C86C6", "#AED8E6", "darkgrey")
plotTheme <- theme(
  panel.background = element_rect(fill = "black"),
  panel.border = element_blank(),
  panel.grid = element_blank(),
  axis.ticks = element_blank(),
  axis.text = element_blank(),
  panel.spacing = unit(0, "cm"),
  strip.background = element_blank())

p1 <- ggplot(subset(sws, chr %in% sprintf("chr%s", 1:9)),
             aes(x = start/1e6, y = propWind, fill = id))+
  geom_area()+
  scale_fill_manual(values = plotCols) +
  facet_grid(.~ gsub("chr","",chr), scale = "free", space = "free") +
  scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0.05,0.05))+
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0.005,0.005))+
  plotTheme +
  labs(x = "Chromosomes (scaled by physical size; 5Mb windows, 1Mb steps)",
       y = "Cumulative % of Sequence")
p2 <- ggplot(subset(sws, !chr %in% sprintf("chr%s", 1:9)),
             aes(x = start/1e6, y = propWind, fill = id))+
  geom_area()+
  scale_fill_manual(values = plotCols) +
  facet_grid(.~gsub("chr","",chr), scale = "free", space = "free") +
  scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0.05,0.05))+
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0.005,0.005))+
  plotTheme +
  labs(x = "Chromosomes (scaled by physical size; 5Mb windows, 1Mb steps)",
       y = "Cumulative % of Sequence")
gridExtra::grid.arrange(p1, p2, nrow = 2)
